Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working on the marketing analyst team at Bellabeat, a high-tech manufacturer of health-focused products for women. Bellabeat is a successful small company, but they have the potential to become a larger player in the global smart device market. Urška Sršen, cofounder and Chief Creative officer of Bellabeat, believes that analyzing smart device fitness data could help unlock new growth opportunities for the company. You have been asked to focus on one of Bellabeat’s products and analyze smart device data to gain insight into how consumers are using their smart devices. The insights you discover will then help guide marketing strategy for the company. You will present your analysis to the Bellabeat executive team along with your high-level recommendations for Bellabeat’s marketing strategy.

Definition of the business task.

Identify opportunities to improve Bellabeat’s marketing strategy through the analysis of smart devices usage.

Stakeholders and application of the results

The main stakeholders are the Chief creative officer, Miss Srsen, the executive team and the marketing team. The findings of the analysis could be used to introduce or improve the ways customers use Bellabeat’s devices and the ways such value is communicated by the marketing team.

Description of all data sources used

The only data source used is FitBit Fitness Tracker Data. The data has been retrived from Kaggle and was made available through Mobius, I downloaded it and stored in my computer. Go to the dataset. The data is open source under the licence CC0, so it’s of public domain and no copyright applies to it. According to the provider, “this dataset generated by respondents to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 03.12.2016-05.12.2016. Thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring.” It consists of 18 .csv files. Data about steps, sleep, activity, calories, intensities per minute, per hour and per day.

The sample is limited to 33 people at most and lacks any information about the population, the risk of encountering bias is high. It was collected 8 years ago and is far from being comprehensive. The data integrity is not solid enough for the results to meet scientific standards and also gaining statistically significant insight could be challenging.

Analysis process: description

I chose to carry out this project using exclusively R, to explore the wide range of possible actions that this language and its packages provide. After defining the business task and checking all the resources available (as done above), a data analyst should plan its analysis step by step. First of all the data needs to be prepared and processed. Then it can be analyzed and visualized, so that the insights are ready to be shared with stakeholders. Most times analysts are also required to act on their findings and find ways to apply them to the business.

The table weight_raw only has 8 unique IDs, making the sample size too small for any finding obtained to be meaningful. Similar considerations could be made about the sleep_raw table, as it does not reach the recommended minimum treshold of sample size >=30. As the other sample sizes are not much larger (24 vs 33) and having clear that findings coming from sleep_raw may not be considered statistically significant, I will still have a look at the table.

remove(weight_raw)

I notice that sleep_raw’s column SleepDay is in a datetime format, with the time having no meaning as it is always “12:00:00”. I want to convert it to a date type column.

sleep_raw$datetimesleep <- as.POSIXct(sleep_raw$SleepDay, format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M")
sleep_raw$date <- as.Date(sleep_raw$datetimesleep)

Let’s check the conversion succedeed and then remove SleepDay and datetimesleep.

Let’s continue the cleaning routine

Cleaning column names and checking for NAs and duplicates.

First of all, it is a good idea to change the name columns SleepDay and ActivityDate into a more consistent “date”.

activity_raw <- activity_raw %>% 
  rename(date = ActivityDate)
sleep_raw <- sleep_raw %>% 
  rename(date = SleepDay)

Now let’s convert the other column names to lower case as well.

clean_names(activity_raw)
activity_raw <- rename_with(activity_raw, tolower)
clean_names(sleep_raw)
sleep_raw <- rename_with(sleep_raw, tolower)
clean_names(hourly_summary)
hourly_summary <- rename_with(hourly_summary, tolower)

Let’s deal with duplicates.

sum(duplicated(activity_raw))
## [1] 0
sum(duplicated(hourly_summary))
## [1] 0
sum(duplicated(sleep_raw))
## [1] 3

Table sleep_raw seems to have 3 duplicates. Let’s remove them as well as NAs.

sleep <- sleep_raw %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  drop_na()

Let’s check if the duplicates were removed and consequently remove sleep_raw.

if(sum(duplicated(sleep)) == 0) remove(sleep_raw)

Let’s drop NAs for the other tables as well

activity <- activity_raw %>% 
  drop_na()
remove(activity_raw)
hourly_summary <- hourly_summary %>% 
  drop_na()

The columns “date” in each of the tables are in the incorrect data type “chr”. I need to fix this using as.Date().

sleep$date <- as.Date(sleep$date, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
activity$date <- as.Date(activity$date, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
hourly_summary$date <- as.Date(hourly_summary$date, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
The cleaning process is basically over.

daily_summary <- merge(sleep, activity, by = c("id", "date"))

remove(sleep)

The same doesn’t apply to activity. I merged the two tables based on common columns only, therefore some observations available in activity were not inclued in the new table. I will therefore keep the source table, as I expect it to possibly be useful later.

Analysis

Relationship between hours of sleep and the amount of steps

As the first step, I would like to explore the relationship between the hours of sleep and the daily steps. If the correlation is strongly positive (close to 1), long sleepers are more likely to walk more. If it is strongly negative (close to -1), it means that people who sleep less tend to walk more.

cor(daily_summary$totalsteps, daily_summary$hoursasleep)
## [1] -0.1903439
steps_vs_sleep <- ggplot(daily_summary) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = totalsteps, y = hoursasleep)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = totalsteps, y = hoursasleep))+
  labs(title = "Total steps vs hours of sleep")
print(steps_vs_sleep)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

The correlation is slightly negative. We can exlclude that people that sleep more walk more.

Looking at the graph, I notice how people that sleep way above average are walking way less than average. I question how this is impacting the results.

I decide to divide the observations in three sleep_type groups: belowrecommended (<6.5 hours), recommended (between 6.5 and 9 hours) and aboverecommended (>9 hours). Reference: Healthline.com

I want to check how the average steps change between the groups.

daily_summary <- daily_summary %>% 
mutate(sleep_type = case_when(
  hoursasleep < 6.5 ~ "below",
  hoursasleep >= 6.5 & hoursasleep <= 9 ~ "recommended",
  hoursasleep > 9 ~ "above"
))

It could also be useful to know how many observations fall in each group.

count_sleep <- daily_summary %>% 
  count(sleep_type) %>% 
  mutate(share_total = round(n/(sum(n)), 3))
print(count_sleep)
##    sleep_type   n share_total
## 1       above  39       0.095
## 2       below 136       0.332
## 3 recommended 235       0.573

Now let’s see the avereage steps per group and the correlation per group.

sleep_type_summary <- daily_summary %>%
  group_by(sleep_type) %>%
  summarise(correlation = cor(totalsteps, hoursasleep), averagesteps = 
              mean(totalsteps), averagesleep = mean(hoursasleep)) %>% 
  arrange(averagesleep)
print(sleep_type_summary)
## # A tibble: 3 × 4
##   sleep_type  correlation averagesteps averagesleep
##   <chr>             <dbl>        <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1 below            0.0902        9532.         4.89
## 2 recommended     -0.0698        8306.         7.67
## 3 above           -0.410         6226.        10.2

The tables shows a negative correlation between hours of sleep and steps for where the sleep exceeds 9 hours. Little to no correlation is shown for the observations where the sleep is less than 9 hours.

Sleeping less then recommended does not negatively impact the amount of steps taken during the day, actually the the average total steps are higher when the hours of sleep are less then the recommended amount (6.5 hours).

avgsteps_by_sleeptype <- ggplot(sleep_type_summary) + 
  geom_col(aes(x=sleep_type, y=averagesteps, fill = sleep_type)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30)) + 
  labs(title = "Average daily steps by amount of sleep", 
       subtitle = "Recommended sleep is between 6.5 and 9 hours")
print(avgsteps_by_sleeptype)

Let’s check the scatterplot again, using different colors for the sleep_type

steps_vs_sleep_group_col <- ggplot(daily_summary) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = totalsteps, y = hoursasleep, color = sleep_type)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = totalsteps, y = hoursasleep))+
  labs(title = "Total daily steps vs amount of sleep", subtitle = "Colored for type of sleep")
print(steps_vs_sleep_group_col)

And then using facets to divide them

steps_vs_sleep_group_fac <-ggplot(daily_summary) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = totalsteps, y = hoursasleep, color = sleep_type)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = totalsteps, y = hoursasleep)) +
  facet_wrap(~sleep_type) +
  labs(title = "Total daily steps vs amount of sleep", subtitle = "Grouped by type of sleep")
print(steps_vs_sleep_group_fac)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Definition of user categories

Another useful analysis could be identifying type of users by their average activity (steps), their average hours of sleep and their average calories.

daily_average <- daily_summary %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  summarise (mean_daily_steps = mean(totalsteps), 
             mean_daily_calories = mean(calories), mean_daily_sleep = mean(hoursasleep))

Let’s assign some categories to the users based on these variables. Based on average steps, users will be sedentary (<6000), active (6000 >= x <=10000) or very active (>10000).

daily_average <- daily_average %>% 
  mutate(activity_lev = case_when(
    mean_daily_steps < 6000 ~ "Sedentary",
    mean_daily_steps >= 6000 & mean_daily_steps <= 10000 ~ "Active",
    mean_daily_steps > 10000 ~ "Very active"
  ))

The sleep categories could be the same used earlier, but these time they will apply to the average sleep for each ID and not to single observations.

daily_average <- daily_average %>% 
mutate(sleep_lev = case_when(
  mean_daily_sleep < 6.5 ~ "undersleeper",
  mean_daily_sleep >= 6.5 & mean_daily_sleep <= 9 ~ "adequate sleeper",
  mean_daily_sleep > 9 ~ "oversleeper"
))

It’s difficult to interpret data about calories without information about the age, weight, gender and job of the user. Therefore I prefer to focus on the other information. Let’s finally define the different user types by merging the coulumns.

I want therefore to define the user types only based on their activity level. I will use the original activity table for this, as the data is more complete than the data in daily_summary. I will create a summary of the activity based on the ID and then assign a user type

activity_user <- activity %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  summarise (avgsteps = mean(totalsteps), 
             avgcalories = mean(calories), 
             avgtotdistance = mean(totaldistance),
             time_avgveryactive= mean(veryactiveminutes),
             time_avgfairlyactive= mean(fairlyactiveminutes),
             time_avglightlyactive= mean(fairlyactiveminutes),
             time_avgsedentary= mean(sedentaryminutes))

activity_user <- activity_user %>% 
  mutate(user_type = case_when(
    avgsteps < 6000 ~ "Sedentary",
    avgsteps >= 6000 & avgsteps <= 10000 ~ "Active",
    avgsteps > 10000 ~ "Very active"
  ))

Let’s use a bar chart to visualize the user type data

Share of time spent doing activities at different intensity level, on average

As a last analysis, I would like to analyze how much time in a day users spend doing some kind of phisical activity, on average.

activity_time <- activity_user %>% 
  summarise(active = mean(time_avgveryactive), 
            fairly_active = mean(time_avgfairlyactive),
            lightly_active = mean(time_avglightlyactive),
            sedentary = mean(time_avgsedentary),
            no_data = (1440 - active - fairly_active - lightly_active
                       - sedentary),
            sum = (active + fairly_active + lightly_active + sedentary + no_data),
            total_day = 24*60,
                      )

Act on the findings

After defining the main findings, it is necessary to share some suggestions on how these insights could be interpreted and applied to make Bellabeat’s marketing strategy better.

Sundays have the least average total steps. Probably becuase a lot of people do not work nor go out. The company could launch a campaign to incentivize physical activity on sundays. This campaign could be focused on the Bellabeat App and lean on social aspects, as most people associate Sundays to family, friends and rest. The campaign could incentivize lightly active group activities.

  • Explore your neighborhood and meet other people that live there;

  • Go for a walk with your family;

  • Stay fit with your friends;

  • Local Bellabeat events every sunday (or e.g. every first sunday of the month).

The social aspect of the app could be enhanced and promoted.

A similar approach could be taken to incentivise physical activity in the morning, as average steps are particularly low at 6:00 and 7:00. As this time does not provide the opportunity to exploit the socialilty, the campaign should focus more on health and mindfulness.

I found out that there is no data about 27,4% of the minutes in a day (or six hours and a half), probably because users do not wear the product during these hours of the day. This most probably happens at night, but other factors could explain this numbers. Making the devices more comfortable, so they can be easily worn at night and in most situations and places, and making the battery life longer, so that the device needs to be charged less frequently, could increase the wear-time and therefore provide the user with more complete data about their health. The Bellabeat product Leaf is particularly comfortable to wear compared to other smart devices and energy-efficient as well. The marketing for this product could be built on this finding, focusing on comfort and practicality. It should highlight the advantages that come from wearing your smart device 24/7 without even noticing, like getting to know your body better thanks to the completeness of the data.

One third of the users are sedentary, a reward-based marketing campaign could be launched to incentivize physical activity overall. Discounts or special content could be provided to users that satisfy set minimum requirement. An example could be winning a month of free premium subscription by waling more than 6000 steps for 5 days in a row.

One third of the sleep observations were too short or long compared to the recommended sleep duration. A campaign about the importance of sleeping good and for a reasonable time, as well as about monitoring sleep through smart devices should be launched. Sleep related content and features could be added to the Bellabeat app and smart devices.

The analysis could be expanded by using and joining more datasets and also by collecting data about Bellebeat users and possibly product-specigic data.
